# Headless CLI — **mandatory**

## A. External AI (Claude / Codex / Gemini / Qwen)

When work is delegated to **Claude Code**, **OpenAI Codex**, **Gemini CLI**, or **Qwen Code**, execution **must** use **non-interactive (headless) mode only**. The agent **must** run the corresponding CLI via the terminal (e.g. Cursor `Shell`) with the full prompt in the command line — **not** asking the user to paste into another app, and **not** using interactive TUI for automation.

| Tool | **Must use** | **Do not use for automation** |
|------|----------------|--------------------------------|
| Claude Code | `claude -p "…"` | Interactive `claude` without `-p` |
| OpenAI Codex | `codex exec "…"` | Interactive Codex TUI |
| Gemini CLI | `gemini -p "…"` | Interactive `gemini` |
| Qwen Code | `qwen -p "…"` | Interactive `qwen` |

**Note:** In Codex, `-p` is often **profile**, not print — use **`codex exec`** for non-interactive runs.

---

## B. CI / format / autofix — **also headless** (user requirement)

Any **mutating** or **fixer** work that changes files to unblock CI or satisfy linters **must** be executed **inside a headless wrapper**, not by the orchestrator running raw `pnpm` / `prettier` / `eslint --fix` / `ruff format` directly.

**Required pattern** (pick one executor; Claude Code is the default when unsure):

```text
claude -p "cd <REPO_ROOT> && <exact shell commands, e.g. pnpm exec prettier --write path/to/file.md && git status>"
```

or

```text
codex exec "cd <REPO_ROOT> && <same commands>"
```

The orchestrator’s job is to **compose** the quoted string and **invoke** one such command via `Shell` — **not** to run `pnpm exec prettier --write ...` as the top-level command itself.

**Examples of “must wrap”:** `prettier --write`, `eslint --fix`, `ruff check --fix`, `ruff format`, any scripted apply that edits tracked files for CI green.

---

## C. What may still run **directly** (read-only / inspection)

These **do not** need a `claude -p` wrapper:

- **Read-only Git / GitHub**: `git status`, `git log`, `git diff` (no write), `gh run list`, `gh run view --log-failed`
- **Read-only verification** (no file writes): `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit`, `pnpm lint` **without** `--fix`, `pytest`, `vitest run` (assuming tests do not rewrite sources)

If a command might **write** files (including caches outside the rule’s intent), treat it as section **B**.

---

## D. Safety

Do not add `--dangerously-skip-permissions` (or equivalent) unless the user explicitly asks and the environment is trusted.
